Step 1: Calculate the Debt to Equity Ratio.
• Liabilities (from balance sheet) are given as Total Current Liabilities = 5,515,978.61.
• Owner's Equity is given as Total Owner's Equity = 16,146,127.58.
• Debt to Equity Ratio = Liabilities / Owner's Equity = 5,515,978.61 / 16,146,127.58 ≈ 0.3414 ≈ 0.34.

Step 2: Calculate the Net Profit Margin.
• Net Profit (from income statement) = 146,127.58.
• Total Revenue (from income statement) = 863,371.65.
• Net Profit Margin = (Net Profit / Total Revenue) × 100 = (146,127.58 / 863,371.65) × 100 ≈ 16.93%.

Step 3: Calculate the Operating Cash Flow to Current Liabilities Ratio.
• Operating Cash Flow (from cash flow statement, Net Cash Flow from Operating Activities) = –2,419,019.09.
• Current Liabilities (from balance sheet) = 5,515,978.61.
• Ratio = Operating Cash Flow / Current Liabilities = –2,419,019.09 / 5,515,978.61 ≈ –0.4384 ≈ –0.44.

Thus, the final answer is:
{
  "solution": {
    "Debt to Equity Ratio": "0.34", 
    "Net Profit Margin": "16.93%", 
    "operating cash flow to current liabilities ratio": "-0.44"
  }
